```suggestion
    pure <| q(Finset.univ_nonempty (α := $α))
```
Please try to stick to the style guide, though I realize muscle memory can be hard to banish

I think this is better without the `try`/`catch`:
```lean
def proveFinsetNonempty {u : Level} {α : Q(Type u)} (s : Q(Finset $α)) :
    MetaM (Option Q(Finset.Nonempty $s)) := do
  if let .some fv ← findLocalDeclWithType? q(Finset.Nonempty $s) then
    return some (.fvar fv)
  else if let ~q(@univ _ $fi) := s then
    if let .some _no ← trySynthInstanceQ q(Nonempty $α) then
      return some q(Finset.univ_nonempty)
    else
      return none
  else
    return none
```
```lean
@[positivity Finset.sum _ _]
def evalFinsetSum : PositivityExt where eval {u α} zα pα e := do
  match e with
  | ~q(@Finset.sum _ $ι $instα $s $f) =>
    let i : Q($ι) ← mkFreshExprMVarQ q($ι) .syntheticOpaque
    have body : Q($α) := Expr.betaRev f #[i]
    let rbody ← core zα pα body
    -- Try to show that the sum is positive
    let p_pos : Option Q(0 < $e) := ← (do
      let .positive pbody := rbody | pure none -- Fail if the body is not provably positive
      let .some ps ← proveFinsetNonempty s | pure none
      let .some pα' ← trySynthInstanceQ q(OrderedCancelAddCommMonoid $α) | pure none
      assertInstancesCommute
      let pr : Q(∀ i, 0 < $f i) ← mkLambdaFVars #[i] pbody
      return some q(@sum_pos $ι $α $pα' $f $s (fun i _ ↦ $pr i) $ps))
    if let some p_pos := p_pos then
      return .positive p_pos
    else
      let pbody ← rbody.toNonneg
      let pr : Q(∀ i, 0 ≤ $f i) ← mkLambdaFVars #[i] pbody
      let pα' ← synthInstanceQ q(OrderedAddCommMonoid $α)
      assertInstancesCommute
      let proof := q(@sum_nonneg $ι $α $pα' $f $s fun i _ ↦ $pr i)
      proof.check
      return .nonnegative proof
  | _ => throwError "not Finset.sum"
  ```
This has the advantage of not catching anything that you don't expect; for instance, if `mkLambdaFVars` fails somehow, or `(try)SynthInstanceQ` fails rather than finds nothing.

I tried for a bit to get this to work, but no success. Here's a Zulip thread: https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/239415-metaprogramming-.2F-tactics/topic/Calling.20aesop.20from.20a.20tactic.20to.20obtain.20an.20.60Expr.60

Thanks to Jannis' help, I came up with:
```suggestion
-/
def proveFinsetNonempty {u : Level} {α : Q(Type u)} (s : Q(Finset $α)) :
    MetaM (Option Q(Finset.Nonempty $s)) := do
  -- Aesop expects to operate on goals, so we're going to make a new goal.
  let goal ← Lean.Meta.mkFreshExprMVar q(Finset.Nonempty $s)
  let mvar := goal.mvarId!
  -- We want this to be fast, so use only the basic and `Finset.Nonempty` specific rules.
  let rulesets ← Aesop.Frontend.getGlobalRuleSets #[`builtin, `Finset.Nonempty]
  -- Fail if the new goal is not closed.
  let rules ← Aesop.mkLocalRuleSet rulesets { terminal := true, generateScript := false }
  let (remainingGoals, _) ← Aesop.search mvar (.some rules)
  -- Fail if there are open goals remaining, this serves as an extra check for the
  -- Aesop configuration option `terminal := true`.
  if remainingGoals.size > 0 then return none
  Lean.getExprMVarAssignment? mvar
```

With the following extra declarations:
```lean
-- `Finset.Nonempty` rules try to prove that a given finset is nonempty,
-- for use in the `Finset.sum` positivity extension.
declare_aesop_rule_sets [Finset.Nonempty] (default := true)
```
and in a separate file:
```lean
attribute [aesop unsafe apply (rule_sets [Finset.Nonempty])] Finset.univ_nonempty
```
I would argue that the `declare_aesop_rule_sets` line should go into a new file (maybe `Mathlib/Data/Finset/Attr.lean`?) and the `attribute` can directly go onto the declaration of `Finset.univ_nonempty`.
(It is still an annoyance that environment extensions only become visible after importing!)
Where should `proveFinsetNonempty` itself live?
I'm putting it in `Data.Finset.Basic` for now. I will want it available for the `Finset.card` extension.
Can you add a test that sums over `Empty` too?

I suppose you were right that the ruleset name and the predicate name were confusing! This was the ruleset name, not the predicate name:
```suggestion
  let rulesets ← Aesop.Frontend.getGlobalRuleSets #[`builtin, `finsetNonempty]
```

To debug this, I did `set_option trace.Tactic.positivity.failure true` and saw:
```
[Tactic.positivity.failure] no such rule set: 'Finset.Nonempty'
      (Use 'declare_aesop_rule_set' to declare rule sets.
       Declared rule sets are not visible in the current file; they only become visible once you import the declaring file.)
```

:facepalm:

Point made
Does this fail in the monadic sense, or in the sense of hitting the  `return none` below?

This is a monadic failure afaict. So you mean it should be:
```suggestion
  -- Fail if the new goal is not closed.
  let rules ← Aesop.mkLocalRuleSet rulesets { terminal := true, generateScript := false }
  let (remainingGoals, _) ← Aesop.search mvar (.some rules) <|> return .none
```
I agree it's probably cleaner returning `none`
Actually this is incorrect syntax and I'm not sure what the correct one is (or if it even makes sense here).

Sorry! The following works on my machine:
```suggestion
  -- Fail if the new goal is not closed.
  let rules ← Aesop.mkLocalRuleSet rulesets { terminal := true, generateScript := false }
  let (remainingGoals, _) ←
    try Aesop.search mvar (.some rules)
    catch _ => return none
```
